defaultWritten evidence submitted by defaultDeightondefault Pierce Glynn (LAI 0034)defaultThis document is submitted on behalf of Deighton
default Pierce Glynn solicitors to address the Government’s proposals to transform legal aid
default, particularly on the issue of the residence test
default. 
defaultDeighton Pierce Glynn is a national law firm which is committed to using 
defaultthe law to enforce the rights of the disadvanta
defaultged of society, hold the state to account for its actions, challenge discrimination and fight human rights and environmental abuses.  
defaultResidence testdefaultThe government’s
default belief that legal aid should be prioritised for those who have a sufficiently strong conn
defaultection to the UK
default is erroneous and misconceived.
default 
defaultThe real issue is that of the jurisdiction or reach of the law impacting upon a person’s life. 
defaultThe fact that a person may not be lawfully resident does not somehow diminish the gravity of the consequences for
default that person if he or she is adversely affected by the actions of the UK State. 
default 
defaultThe conformity of the law for those affected by it within the ambit of its jurisdiction was stated by Lord Scarman in R v SSHD ex.p Khawaja [1982] 1WLR 321 
default              
default67. ……Every pers
defaulton within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of our laws. There is 
default              
defaultno distinction between British nationals and others. He who is subject to English law is 
default              
defaultentitled to its protection….’ 
defaultWhilst 
defaultKhawaja’s
default case concerned liberty it was the indivi
defaultsible concept of those being within the jurisdiction of the English law being entitled to its protection that was in issue.  Further, it is not just the mere existence of the protection of the law which engages the rule of 
defaultlaw 
defaultbut effective access to it; l
defaultegal protection which is not accessible 
defaultrenders such protection meaningless
default. 
defaultThe government is of the view that the exceptional fun
defaultding regime adequately provides
default for those excluded 
defaultby the residence test to apply for legal aid.  This 
defaultis not correct becaus
defaulte t
defaulthe bar to qualifying for exceptional funding has been set far too high
default to render any potential access to funding by this route ineffective
default. 
defaultThe exceptional funding guidance
default 
defaultstates that, 
default‘the overarching question to consider is whether the withholding of
default legal aid would make the assertion of the claim practically impossible or lead to an obvious unfairness in proceedings.
default’
default This is a very high threshold.
default The guidance 
defaultpositively discourages the grant of funding
default, does not adequately allow for urgent cases an
defaultd excludes those with private and family life reasons (Article 8 ECHR) for needing to remain in the UK and seeking support. 
defaultThere is also a significant amount of non-funded work which would necessary making this process to be financially unsustainable ove
defaultr time; this is because the rates of pay for publicly funded work mean that it is unsustainable to do much, if any, non-chargeable work. 
defaultThe effect of the test for exceptional funding is to create a two tier system for legal aid (a non-migrant service and
default a migrant service) with the latter being much more difficult if not impossible to access.  This is obviously unfair where the legal issue requiring resolution is just the same with the adverse consequences even harsher for the migrant applicant. On its fa
defaultce such a system is 
defaultdiscriminatory which is not jus
defaulttified in all the circumstances.  T
defaulthere needs to be a heightened sense of fairness when dealing with vulnerable groups such as unaccompanied minors 
defaultThe residence test will 
defaultrequire suppliers and the Legal 
defaultAid Agency to carefully assess applicants’ immigrations status. This is a time consuming and complicated task. The government has grossly underestimated the practical implication of implementing the residence test.  It applies
default to 
defaulteveryone
default with a civil lega
defaultl aid case (save possibly those people with 
defaultcases
default of the kind that are listed under para
defaultgraph
default 125 of Appendix B to Transforming Legal Aid Next steps). Most will pass it, provided they can prove past lawful residence (and there are problems for many) and ar
defaulte physically present. 
