defaultI
defaultn this one year alone, each of these 729,483 acts of assistance would have 
defaultneeded to be preceded by a residence test administered by their solicitors, before any funding was available.
default&#xa0;
defaultThose that the residence test is proposed to exclude from access to legal aid are often extremely vulnerable and many are unable to leave the UK 
defaultthrough no fault of their own. The proposal will leave them without a legal remedy when their fundamental human rights are at stake, undermining the rule of law in the UK, and the “access to a fair open justice system” referred to in the introduction to co
defaultnsultation. Legal aid ensures access to basic legal entitlements to housing or subsistence. Without legal aid, many will be left street homeless and without sufficient food, including families, people fleeing domestic violence and people with physical or m
defaultental disabilities, breaching their fundamental human rights. There will be an increased burden on safety net public authorities such as the police, A and E departments and social services.  
defaultIt is a poor use of resources to transfer the duty of the state 
defaultto cater for the needs of vulnerable litigants in person, who speak English as a second language, onto the courts. Similarly, the requirement for 
defaultevery
default legal aid applicant to satisfy an immigration and residence test is disproportionate. Eligible applicant
defaults may not have the correct documents. Many legal aid suppliers do not have the skills to fairly apply such a test. The increased visibility of a migrant community which is street homeless because it cannot easily access social welfare provision risks damag
defaulting race relations. The proposals are open to challenge on discrimination grounds, particularly in relation to EU nationals.
defaultDetailed points
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposed residence and immigration test does not necessarily identify the claimed objective or those with a 
defaultstrong connection to the UK. For example, a person may have been born in the UK and lived here all their life but not have leave to remain;
default&#xa0;
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe measure proposed will have a disproportionate adverse effect on legal aid applicants with a strong connection t
defaulto the UK by subjecting them to an unnecessary immigration and residence test. The client group in receipt of legal aid is primarily a vulnerable group. It 
defaultincludes: disabled people, people with mental health needs and learning disabilities, women leaving d
defaultomestic violence or trafficking, and homeless families. It is inappropriate to subject those in this group, who are otherwise eligible for welfare and support services, to an immigration and residence test. They may be in urgent need of legal services but 
defaultunable to produce the relevant documentation. As a result, essential legal aid advice and representation may be refused or delayed, causing extreme hardship;
default&#xa0;
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAssessing immigration and residence issues is a specialist skill. The 
defaultsubmissions of the Immigration Law Practitioners’ Association (ILPA)
default in relation to the c
defaultomplexity of this are adopted and so not repeated here. An applicant may have lea
defaultve to remain even though it is not referred to in a document. Errors will be made, resulting in those who are entitled being excluded; 
default&#xa0;
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs stated above, the issue of lawfulness of residence is complex. It may be the subject-matter of the case, requiring f
defaulturther investigation in order to assess it. For example, a person may have been refused homelessness assistance, healthcare, community care, asylum support etc.  because they were treated as ineligible because of their immigration status. They need legal a
defaultid to be able to get advice on whether those decisions were correct and to make appropriate challenges. These challenges often turn out to be successful at the end of the case. Who will decide whether the person is eligible for legal aid at the beginning o
defaultf the case, when a lot of investigation needs to be carried out into the assessment of the person’s immigration status? The LAA? The ‘non-immigration’ specialist solicitor? 
default&#xa0;
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe applicant may not have leave to remain due to delay or error on the part of U
defaultKBA. Legal aid may be needed to challenge these failures (see case study below);
