defaultThe 
defaultgovernment’s equality impa
defaultct assessment (EIA)
default is completely inadequate. It does not  reference the statistics, which the LAA collects for gender, race and disability status of legal aid applicants and consider the impact of the proposals on this group but simply makes a vague compa
defaultrison between British and 
defaultnon-British
default nationals. This is a test which will also require British nationals to produce evidence of lawful residence etc. and there is no consideration of how the test will impact on protected groups within that category, e.g. 
defaultif they have a cognitive impairment or are not British by origin. In relation to justification, there is no evidence either as to the impact or as to what the costs-saving is.  Nor is there any evidence or consideration of potential additional costs e.g. t
defaulto providers/the LAA in conducting the test, or to other public bodies. 
defaultIn relati
defaulton to mitigation
default, we would propose there should be an exemption from the test for protected groups, or where urgent legal aid is needed e.g. to apply for an injunction as part
default of a judicial review to enable a woman fleeing domestic violence and her children to access emergency housing. Exceptional funding is not an adequate form of mitigation since there is no funding to apply for it, and it delays the process. Finally, there i
defaults no detail on how ECHR or EU requirement will be met, so the consultation does not allow respondents to assess or consider this issue.
default&#xa0;defaultPaying for permission work in judicial review casesdefaultThe government asked at Q5 of 
defaultits
default consultation document ‘do you agr
defaultee with the proposal that providers should only be paid for work carried out on an application for judicial review, including a request for reconsideration of the application at a hearing, the renewal hearing, or an onward permission appeal to the Court of
default Appeal, if permission is granted by the Court (but that reasonable disbursements are paid in any event)?  Please give reasons.’
defaultSummary
defaultNo, we do not agree with this proposal.  
defaultReason 1: Clients will be unable to secure legally-aided representation even defaultfor strong casesdefault defaultThe impact assessment acknowledge
defaults
default that MOJ has 
defaultput forward
default this proposal 
default(
defaultand the Secretary of State has announced 
defaulton the Today programme
default his
default 
defaultintention to implement it)
default without knowing what the impact will be. MOJ states that the impact 
defaultwill depend on the supplier response. We agree.
default 
defaultDeighton Pierce Glynn is one of the largest, most successful and highly-regarded solicitors firms conducting judicial review cases for claimants
default.
default 
defaultA 
defaulthigh proportion of the judicial review claims we bring are f
defaultunded by legal aid. 
defaultWe have costed the impact of this proposal. Our clear conclusion is that it will render our legally-aided judicial review work unviable. In particular, because of the risk that even in strong cases in which successful outcomes are secur
defaulted the work we carry out will go unpaid (see reasons 2 to 7 below). Therefore our response will be to cease to represent members of the public seeking to bring judicial review claims who cannot afford to pay us. The availability of CFAs does not ameliorate
default the access to justice impacts of this proposal in any way given the failure to implement Jackson’s LJ’s proposal for qualified one-way costs shifting in judicial review and because in judicial review an inter partes order does not necessarily follow even 
defaultif the client secures a successful outcome. In light of this, it is clear to us that the proposal will unlawfully restrict access to justice and legally aided representation. It is also appears that the proposal has been prompted by complaints by Ministers
default in other departments about their decision-making being subject to judicial scrutiny. The proposals represent a serious and unjustified attack on the rule of law.
