default&#xa0;
defaultBorderline casesdefaultAt 
defaultQ6
default the question was asked
default. 
default‘
defaultDo you agree with the proposal that legal aid should be removed for all cases
default 
defaultassessed as ha
defaultving ‘borderline’ prospects of success? Please give reasons.
default’
defaultSummary
default&#xa0;
defaultNo, we do not agree that legal aid should be removed from all cases assessed as having ‘borderline’ prospects of success.  Funding for borderline cases is crucial to allow difficult 
defaultareas of law to develop, particularly those affecting large numbers of vulnerable people whose rights are not already protected.
default&#xa0;
defaultDetailed points
default&#xa0;
default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe current arrangements only allow a very limited number of borderline cases to go ahead where the case has 
defaultsignificant wider public interest, is of overwhelming importance to the client or relates to a significant human rights breach; each of these concepts have specific definitions and thus funding on borderline cases is already very focussed and strictly cont
defaultrolled.  This system was established to recognise that there are a small number of claims that are so important they should be brought, even if the prospects of success are borderline;
default&#xa0;
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMoreover, this small number of cases enables the law to develop to inc
defaultrease the protection of the rights of the most vulnerable, for example severely-disabled people who wish to 
defaultexercise their “right to die”, those detained abroad by British security services, and so on.  Withdrawing funding from these cases would prevent th
defaulte rights of the most vulnerable being tested – and extended – before the courts;
default&#xa0;
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are numerous cases in which the High Court and the Court of Appeal have found against a claimant, who then succeeds before the Supreme Court by a majority; by definitio
defaultn these could be classed as “borderline” but succeeded.  Such cases would no longer be funded if this proposal were to go ahead; and
default&#xa0;
default(d)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe consultation document does not explain how much money this proposal will save.  It refers to the number of cases but d
defaultoes not provide any detail as to the costs incurred by the Legal Aid Fund, or how many succeeded and what benefits accrued to the claimants and others.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnnex K – Equalities impactdefault (consultation questions 34 to 35) in relation to the proposals under Q5 anddefault Q6default&#xa0;
defaultSummary
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Equalities Impact document that appears at Annex K of the consultation paper does not support the claim that the MoJ has had due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, advance equality of opportunity or foster good relations, as 
defaultrequired by s.149 Equality Act 2010.  We therefore do not agree that MoJ has correctly identified the range of impacts, nor their extent, for the reasons set out below.
default&#xa0;
defaultDetailed points
default&#xa0;
default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe inevitable discrimination (described as “disproportionate impact”
default at paragraph 4.4) that will be caused is apparently justified by the need to limit the cost of legal aid and to ensure public confidence in the legal aid system (see para 4.2).  In relation to the proposals concerning payment for permission stage work, bo
defaultrderline cases and the residence test, very little or no information has been provided as to how much money will be saved, nor has any information been provided as to the apparent lack of public confidence in the system, or how these proposals will restore
default confidence.  If the Government seeks to justify this disproportionate impact on the basis that these proposals represent a proportionate means of achieving a legitimate aim, the evidence is missing to support this conclusion.  Thus, the rationale and just
defaultification behind the proposals is flawed and the public sector equality duty is not met;
default&#xa0;
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt paragraph 4.6 the document states that “for those proposals directly affecting the remuneration of providers, we do not consider that they are likely to have a dir
defaultect impact on clients” and that an adverse effect on service provision is unlikely.  There is no evidence referred to in the consultation paper to support these assertions.  It is self-evident that if providers are not paid, they will not bring cases; this
default will have a direct impact on clients (for example disabled people challenging community care decisions) and it will affect service provision as providers will stop bringing cases and some will go out of business;
default&#xa0;
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 5.4 of Annex K deals with the 
defaultpaying for permission work in JR cases proposal; this makes no mention of the obvious impact on disabled people if their representatives will not get paid for cases that settle pre-permission.  This section asserts that: “
defaultWhere a provider refuses to take a
default case on a legally aided basis, clients may choose to proceed privately and bear the financial risk of the application themselves
default.”  This is a bizarre suggestion; these are legally-aided clients who by definition have no money; they cannot pay their repres
defaultentatives, nor could they risk an adverse costs order; and
default&#xa0;
default(d)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 5.5 of Annex K deals with the proposal for removing legal aid for borderline cases and states that this is a proportionate means of achieving the legitimate aims of saving money and ensuri
defaultng public confidence.  However, there is no analysis of the costs that will be saved, how this will increase public confidence, nor any consideration of the subject matter of the cases, what the outcome has been or the wider impact of such test case litiga
defaulttion succeeding.  Thus, again, the evidence is missing to support the assertion that this is a proportionate means of achieving a legitimate aim; this breaches s.149 EA 2010 as “due regard” has not been had.
